name: pipeline construction, natural gas, long distance, low capacity, onshore | pipeline, natural gas, long distance, low capacity, onshore | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/9074/documentation

It is assumed that half of the pipelines are disposed in a discharge at the end of life, the other half stays in the soil. The life time of the pipeline is 40 years.;[This dataset was already contained in the ecoinvent database version 2. It was not individually updated during the transfer to ecoinvent version 3. Life Cycle Impact Assessment results may still have changed, as they are affected by changes in the supply chain, i.e. in other datasets. This dataset was generated following the ecoinvent quality guidelines for version 2. It may have been subject to central changes described in the ecoinvent version 3 change report (http://www.ecoinvent.org/database/ecoinvent-version-3/reports-of-changes/), and the results of the central updates were reviewed extensively. The changes added e.g. consistent water flows and other information throughout the database. The documentation of this dataset can be found in the ecoinvent reports of version 2, which are still available via the ecoinvent website. The change report linked above covers all central changes that were made during the conversion process.]



This dataset describes the infrastructure needed for a long-distance pipeline onshore with a capacity from average 0.8e6 Sm3/h gas including material requirements, construction and disposal. Helicopter flights for inspection are included.
category: F:Construction/42:Civil engineering/422:Construction of utility projects/4220:Construction of utility projects

processDocumentation.geographyDescription: The data represents an average European pipeline (capacity: 0.8 Mio. Nm3 gas per hour).
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: The material quantities are calculated on the basis of the geometry of the pipeline (diameter 950mm, thickness 10 mm).
